############ Scaling ##############
@@ Current:
3 Pods

@@ Scale Up:
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl scale rs nginx-rs --replicas=5

@@ Verify:
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl get pods

@@ Expected:
5 Pods

@@ Scale Down
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl scale rs nginx-rs --replicas=2

@@ Observe:
Extra Pods removed
Why Scaling Matters

@@ Real Scenario:
Normal Traffic = 2 Pods
Black Friday Sale = 20 Pods
Scaling handles increased load.


###########################################
######## Accidental Pod Deletion #####

Production Incident
@@ Developer accidentally runs:
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl delete pod --all

@@ What happens?
ReplicaSet detects:

Desired = 3
Current = 0

Action:

Creates 3 new Pods automatically.

Application recovers.

@@ Investigation Commands
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl get rs
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl describe rs nginx-rs

@@ Look at:
Events
Current Replicas
Desired Replicas

######################################
######### Label Mismatch Problem ##########

@@ Create a Pod manually:

labels:
  app: apache

ReplicaSet expects:

app: nginx

@@ Question:

Will ReplicaSet manage this Pod?
=> No.

Because selector does not match.

Verify:

[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl get pods --show-labels

@@ Learning
This is one of the most common interview questions.

#######################################
######## Worker Node Failure ##########

@@ Architecture:
Worker-1
  Pod-A
  Pod-B

Worker-2
  Pod-C

Worker-1 crashes.

@@ Result:
Pod-A Lost
Pod-B Lost

@@ ReplicaSet notices:
Desired = 3
Running = 1

@@ Kubernetes schedules:
New Pods on Worker-2

Application survives.

